"1178–Female":"1178–Zesnulá","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","about 1228":"okolo 1228","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Anglie",",England.":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Salemon, England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Withington, Cheshire, England":"Withington, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1210–1252":"1210–1252","1205–1228":"1205–1228","1228–1301":"1228–1301","1174–Male":"1174–Afdød","1178–Female":"1178–Afdød","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","about 1228":"omkring 1228","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England",",England.":"England, United Kingdom","Salemon, England":"England, United Kingdom","Withington, Cheshire, England":"Withington, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1210–1252":"1210–1252","1205–1228":"1205–1228","1228–1301":"1228–1301","1174–Male":"1174–Overleden","1178–Female":"1178–Overleden","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","about 1228":"circa 1228","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England",",England.":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Salemon, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Withington, Cheshire, England":"Withington, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1210–1252":"1210–1252","1205–1228":"1205–1228","1228–1301":"1228–1301","1174–Male":"1174–Deceased","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","about 1228":"about 1228","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England",",England.":"England, United Kingdom","Salemon, England":"England, United Kingdom","Withington, Cheshire, England":"Withington, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salemon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Emanuel, Akiva, Maier, Mayer, Moshe, Tali, Tziporah, Uzi, Yehuda.","Jewish, Hungarian, German, Dutch, Polish, and English (Middlesex); Czech and Slovak (also <b>Šalamon</b>); Slovenian and Croatian (mainly <b>Šalamon</b>): from the personal name <i>Salamon</i> or <i>Šalamon</i>, local variant or equivalent of   Solomon   or, as in the case of the Slovenian name, of   Salomon  .","Italian: from a northeastern regional variant of the personal name   Salamone   ‘Solomon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Salak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Wasyl, Zofia.","Czech and Hungarian (<b>Salák</b>); Slovak (also <b>Salák</b>, <b>Šalak</b>, <b>Šalák</b>): from a pet form of the personal name   Salamon  , in Slovak also <i>Šalamon</i> (see   Solomon  ).","Polish: patronymic from a short form of the personal name   Salomon   or   Salamon   (see   Solomon  )."]},{"name":"Solomon","meanings":["Jewish, English, Scottish, Dutch, Swedish, French, Portuguese, Romanian, Ethiopian, and Eritrean; Spanish (<b>Solomón</b>): from a vernacular form of the Biblical Hebrew personal name <i>Shelomo</i>, a derivative of <i>shalom</i> ‘peace’. The name <i>Solomon</i> has for generations been a popular Jewish name and was also fairly widespread in the Middle Ages among Christians. In the Bible it is the name of King David's successor, noted for his wisdom; among Christians it was therefore also used as a nickname for a man who was considered wise. The spelling <i>Solomon</i> is used in the King James Bible of 1611, which is why this is the standard form of the name in modern English, but spellings with <i>Sal-</i> were more usual across continental Europe, the 1534 Lutheran Bible rendering it as <i>Salomo</i> and the 1560 Geneva Bible as   Salomon  . From the 7th century the spelling <i>Salomon</i> is recorded as a Christian personal name in France, where it was the name of several saints including a Breton king martyred in 874. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages (see   Salomon  ,   Salamon  ). See also   Salmon   1. — Note: Since Ethiopians and Eritreans do not have hereditary surnames, the Ethiopian and Eritrean name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Salaman","meanings":["Jewish: variant of   Salamon  ."]},{"name":"Saliga","meanings":["Slovak (<b>Šaliga</b>): perhaps a derivative of a short form of the old personal name <i>Šalamún</i> (see   Salamon  ). Alternatively, it may be of Polish origin (see below).","In some cases also an Americanized form of Polish <b>Sałyga</b>: nickname from the dialect noun <i>sałyga</i> ‘kind of dish usually made of saltbush’ or verb <i>sałygać</i> ‘to eat with relish’; less probably a derivative of a short form of the personal name   Salamon  . This surname is mainly found in Masovian Voivodeship."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Salemon of Withington was born in 1210, in Withington, Cheshire, England, his father, Benet Gernet Salemon, was 37 and his mother, Mabel Fitzurse, was 33. He had at least 1 daughter with Beatrix de Hulme. He died in 1252, in Cheshire, England, at the age of 42, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1210–1252":"1210–1252","1205–1228":"1205–1228","1228–1301":"1228–1301","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England",",England.":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Salemon, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Withington, Cheshire, England":"Withington, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1210–1252":"1210–1252","1205–1228":"1205–1228","1228–1301":"1228–1301","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1178–Female":"1178–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","about 1228":"noin 1228","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England",",England.":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Salemon, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Withington, Cheshire, England":"Withington, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1210